Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, according to the European Community statistics office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, said Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the policy interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, together with higher commodity prices and lower unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject at a later date.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent has been a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has picked up due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Cereal futures market ratings have increased by 88 per cent and soya prices have also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 per cent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 per cent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of the Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December. Thus, since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never seen such a low level of socialist support, namely 13 per cent.
For the faithful voters, the difference would represent, because of the greater determination of the opposition voters, support of more than two thirds (71 per cent) against the support of a fifth (20 per cent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the survey, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two per cent for the entire population.
Of the faithful voters certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been higher, it amounts to 41 per cent and, according to 46 per cent, the situation is rather serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population is planning a worsening and only one tenth is planning an improvement.
Last December, 71 percent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, felt that the Prime Minister was doing his job badly rather than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or much trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the President of Fidesz.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society who believe that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the October riots, 35 per cent of the respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, at present this rate is only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believes that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
To the question concerning the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents replied that they would certainly vote and the additional 20 per cent said that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday," only 55 per cent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent would probably participate. Depending on current intentions, the result of the referendum would not be in doubt.
74 per cent would say no to tuition fees in higher education, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees and 84 per cent would say no to hospital living expenses.
When we look only at the same proportions of those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters respectively would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital living expenses.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs commercial triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, except that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs commercial triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by an average of 16 percent, a value increase well above a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flown off" in major food stores last December, no longer rose sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that the items purchased clearly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value in the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, the value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained close to last year's level, but prices for turkey fillet, walnuts and poppy rose sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found from a kilo to 139 forints only.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre recorded bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints of the recorded bottle included therein.
However, this year, in terms of daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased it by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing the most expensive basket of last year with the cheapest basket of this year, we see a difference of 12 percent while the difference between the cheapest of last year and the most expensive of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, although the impact of the increase in VAT rates was already noted in last year's Christmas prices.
As a result of this process, trade was perplexed, hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
As a result of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the daily basket was so excessive that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of 2006, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so much as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the price of the cheapest one also increased 1,284 forints.
When we brought the two Christmas seasons closer together, we saw a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some basic supplies, the Institute of Statistics has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the latter's daily Basket, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
There are indications that flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get acceptance of the sharp price increase also by multinationals.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
Based on our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the long-preserved food by pallets.
Wednesday morning important tails formed at the crates of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased abruptly.
However, according to our information, the turnover is lower in the provinces, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
Hospital hygienic conditions, insufficient beds, overwork of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the Chief Medical Officer of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected on a man in hospital following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person in a serious car accident left the hospital but shortly afterwards had to return because of an MRSA infection and since then, the doctors have not been able to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Namely, it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop an antibiotic resistant bacterium that will rapidly proliferate in the wrong hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunctioning of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly, small weight patients or patients with a weakened body.
According to the medical director of the hospital János, there is nothing particular about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily lives of hospitals.
We must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we cannot find MRSA only where we are not looking for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
HAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, care workers put rubber gloves and protective masks on and we have antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they carry MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in mode
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and seniors' homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund such examinations.
Most cases only occur if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the Chief Medical Officer of the Epidemiological Centre.
The European Union has strong recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological testing should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, there are significant gaps in hospitals in this area as well.
The MRSA proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, whereas in terms of epidemics, patients should be kept away from each other by at least 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also note that hospitals, in difficult financial situation, are saving money on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is less demonstrably or the spread of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenditure for the social security funds, which is why it is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies as one of its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not drunk.
The official finding regarding the fatal accident caused by the 22nd district commissioner was made.
It can be ruled out that the commissioner of the 22nd district, who has since resigned from his post, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led in a state of intoxication or dizziness, announced Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation which already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving
Last Tuesday, the former head of the 22nd district police station crushed a 55-year-old man who was facing him when he turned, with his own car, on Kossuth Lajos Street in the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(Moreover, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing does not constitute a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code, a car which starts a turn must pass the pedestrians.)
The pedestrian died after being taken to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and applied for his retirement because, according to the police report, the accident upset him very much.
The investigation into this case is carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
An additional €400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of EUR 400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties; this time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also covers budgetary funding for education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, with the remaining EUR 150 million to be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a €50 million innovation contract, the state budget will use this envelope primarily as part of the research and development project to be carried out at Debrecen University.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible amendment of the original contract once Hungary has finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commission of commitment.
Bulgaria, the paradise of the EU real estate market
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is focused on this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or who and who bought on this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re / Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is unquestionably the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap beach houses.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands," the "Sun Coast," the former Sozopol and Nessebar but more and more are looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik area as well.
According to the analysts of Re / Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also increasingly buying in the inexpensive corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, the shops and offices area promises the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of Europe's most attractive golf paradise and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time trying to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we have traditionally met many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re / Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and generally to the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary residences (since last December, Bulgaria has been mentioned as one of the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is composed of commercial investors who buy in the hope of realising value in the medium or long term.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly rising due to growing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The rise in real estate prices is mainly higher than the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the communication from Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Water, the professional meetings are ending on Tuesday, yet Wednesday, after the official opening, the ministers' negotiations on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Map, which is intended to define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol's emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there are intense discussions on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also indicated that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, while it was prepared to sign an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 per cent from 1990 levels by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, excluding emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement has also been signed on aid to developing countries.
The support fund under the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, probably under the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF), said Piacés Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its flagship role in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 from 1990 levels, regardless of the successful signing of the "Post-2012 Agreement," and is prepared to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and / or developing countries are also prepared to make commitments appropriate to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the Kyoto Protocol countries had achieved a total reduction of 5.2 per cent, and all 15 EU members of that time made a commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the period 1985-1987, and our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The issue at stake in Bali is that the long-term international agreement on climate policy needs to be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be delayed after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was underlined in the new report by IPCC, an international scientific body, which has been awarded the UN Nobel Peace Prize for climate change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celcius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army Recruits on YouTube
The British Army units make available on the video-sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First of all, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that was passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan are uploading video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature helmet cameras, are monitored at Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to Londrès where compatriots load them on the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this channel and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence signed up as "defence headquarters" in the spring of 2007 and provides videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the original objective of the air force, the videos were posted on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to inform the general public of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published through this channel costs almost nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, communicated to the BBC's defence consultant Gordon Mackenzie. However, it also inevitably carries a political message, since it justifies in a special form the validity of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been posted on the sharing site which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently embarked on loading these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently by using the America's Army shooting game that can be downloaded for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
