On the other hand, Mónika Lamperth, Minister of Labour, does not officially invite his employees to a Christmas party but to a working meeting at the end of the year.
One hundred and eighty people are expected who will be invited to have coffee and eat doughnuts, the press service said, so the party will cost only 350,000 forints.
Gordon Bajnai, Minister of Local Government, will simply invite his staff to have a drink in the Ministry of Local Government and Territorial Development.
The Ministry of Finance (PM) will host a Christmas party in its large hall with 436 employees expected.
He plans to spend 2,500 forints per guest including a buffet and a glass.
Since the arrival of János Veres, PM employees celebrate Christmas each year in the same way.
No party atmosphere is foreseen, the official character is reinforced not only by the minister's presentation but also by the hour of the party taking place in the afternoon.
The Ministry of Agriculture will hold a reception on 20 January to celebrate the New Year, Christmas will not take place.
The reception will be held at Vajdahunyad Castle, located in Bois de ville, and according to the Ministry's communication, 1,000 forints per person are calculated for the hundred guests.
According to the press service, this will be a very simple cocktail to which only foreign diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
These cocktails, organized every year, are started with a few words of welcome from the Minister followed by a modest meal.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Ministry of Education and Culture do not celebrate Christmas at all, have communicated to [origo] the respective press services.
The press service of the Ministry of the Environment did not know the price of the official Christmas party.
However, more than four hundred people were invited to the festival held at the Museum of Decorative Art.
The forces of the mega strike gather
On Friday, the trade unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form their strike commission, which will be responsible for coordinating Monday's indefinite strike.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the law on health funds, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause important traffic closures as rail traffic will be stopped almost completely and BKV (public transport company) employees will also strike until 1: 00 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the League Trade Unions will announce the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The LIGA-MOSZ strike commission will also be set up as coordinator of Monday's actions.
Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and, from Monday, the organizations joining the strike will stop the work for an indefinite period if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the law on health funds, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the law on health funds, the trade unions will immediately withdraw the call to strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike commissions will meet and decide on the next steps.
According to the Monday agenda of the National Assembly, it is likely that the vote on the Health Caisse Act will take place only late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, major traffic closures are planned: the railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of the public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the road will be blocked as well.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call to strike, the list of these is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations reported an indefinite strike, while others reported a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Railway Union (VDSZSZ) failed to reach an agreement on minimum services, but, as Christmas festivities approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 1: 00 p.m., Budapest airport between 7: 00 a.m. and 9: 00 a.m., the League's Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Unions will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union have called for a strike for two hours and two hours to eight hours respectively.
The Association nationale des médecins will strike in alternance throughout the country, while the Syndicat des employés de la santé et du secteur social (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal on health reform and submit a new concept to social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating retirement to be introduced from next year onwards be introduced in several stages.
The third claim is for a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, that would allow the proper functions to be transferred to the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Railway Union (VDSZSZ), attached to the League Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for Better Hungary), increases, in several respects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning," society points out that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur following the aggravation of the ethnic tension already existing between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary."
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason for this.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings which have based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians."
The problem is compounded, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, due to the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular regarding confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country."
They recall that, following greater publicity given to the reorganisation of the radical and extreme right groups in Hungary since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007, calling themselves the "national self-defence association."
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defence missions (disasters, national defence, defence of the order), armed if necessary, by referring to the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state," they added.
They pointed out that everything was going according to the method which, based on the resentment of the political society and the parties, sought to disguise different political ambitions from a civilian point of view.
The emphasis on civil status and association status therefore serves only to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering such associations in court, but they also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk compared to neighbourhood relations.
