The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law exactly defines the holiday days and around the holidays it has become common to reorganize working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
Festivals are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between days of national and state holidays and days of rest.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year ending and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that waiters can rest quietly.
Moreover, in a year, we have a total of eleven parties marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday in commemoration of the 1848 revolution, as is October 23, which is also the commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, on May 1 is Labour Day and on November 1 and 2, we remember our family and friends who died.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
On the days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely falling on a weekend, according to the schedule, it has become common to reorganize working days in cases where there is only one working day before or after the celebration marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in special regulations on the replacement days of the days preceding or following the holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and their employees, civil servants and persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service companies, as institutions operate continuously and in service, because of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end-of-year holidays: as of December 24, life stops almost throughout the country, as the majority of people tend to work overtime or take vacations that they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around Labour Day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day to have a day off on Friday 2 May.
Another change is scheduled for October 23: Saturday, October 18 will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year will be celebrated, as from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
