Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, this is really an island of freedom.
Anything you expect from your leave can happen if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Palm and all inclusive with servers offering you on the beach pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list in its entirety, but enriched.
But there is only one island on which you will find much more and it is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the bastion of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus described it as the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the repository and trans-shipment of the treasures that the Spaniards had stolen and were transporting to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 1920s.
Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mob, built it, since everything that was a crime in the USA (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, tall buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 1950s of the last century, were circulating on the broad boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
Show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
So what about today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of Havana's Bodeguita.
In the bar of Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will be mixed up with the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since the jigoulis and the fiats once imported have already for a long time, in a climate so salty and wet, rotten.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is noticeably declining, nowhere else in the vicinity is there as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings the money if necessary, its development has the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of the Holguín province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and will be appreciated especially by those who love small trains.
The cane had returned from the plantations in sugar mills on a narrow track by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades, and this is how small locomotives, whose contemporaries are not only in museums, can be seen on the move.
Where to direct his steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the most well-known places.
So there is no need to write a lot about Varadero or Havana.
Otherwise remember that in Hemingway's property, already mentioned, there is a museum and that whoever loves this writer should not miss the visit.
One of the most picturesque corners of Cuba is the Víñales valley to the west of the island.
Exuberant vegetation grows on limestone soil.
Mogotes, calcareous balloons and rocks rise in candlelight from the bottom of the valley, and, with fertile earth caught in their entrails, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense plant carpet.
The valley is the place where Cuban tobacco of the highest quality is probably grown.
You can meet the final shape of this product if you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
Someone may also find it interesting that this is where Major Zeman's Chilean episode was shot.
Trinidad
Old town founded shortly after the Spaniards colonized the island.
It was the market for slaves and sugar that brought him glory and wealth.
Wealth has been embodied in the beauty and showcase-city character of this small city.
Koloniální španělská architektura, výraznė ovlivněná pozdějšími francouzskými osadníky, se za čtyři staletí ffíě, nezměnila.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountain range, is such a remote place that still in the 1950s of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay away.
We didn't build anything, and that's why we didn't demolish anything either, everyone just had a roof over their heads.
If you have more time than an afternoon in Trinidad, then it is also worth seeing interesting places in the vicinity, such as Playa Ancón Beach or the Valley of Sugar.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música, which is animated after sunset and where the music only deafens in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some call this village in the extreme east of Cuba the most beautiful on the island.
This view is certainly already influenced by the path that leads to it.
The two roads leading from Guantánamo must cross high and rugged mountains and cross a landscape almost without marks of human activity.
UNESCO has placed Cuba's eastern patch, thanks to its unspoilt landscape, on the list of world heritage.
The best chocolate is made in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in fact, it was born about a hundred years after Columbus's journey) and from the hill where the old castle-fort and the present hotel El Castillo are held, there are several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountain massif, the Bay of Sows and the island Isla de Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the shrine of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, Santeria, African religions practiced by the descendants of the former slaves, about all this a quantity of pages could be filled.
Only, as they say, it's better to see once.
In Afghanistan, allies are passive, say Americans
The lack of troops and necessary equipment, according to the United States, affects the conduct of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defence Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the years to come.
The mission to Afghanistan is not proceeding as it should, agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland, representatives of countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
In addition to the growing opposition on the part of the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are now also discussing future plans and the coordination of allies.
While the United States has called this week through Defence Minister Robert Gates for NATO troops to become more active, Britain has given priority to strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and stepping up development assistance.
"Developments in Afghanistan are perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other being to allow the inhabitants to start a new development of the economy and security themselves, "said the British defense minister Des Browne to the BBC channel.
Ninety per cent
Afghan insurgent activity is, according to US military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions has increased by 27 per cent compared to last year, up to 60 per cent in the southern Helmand province.
NATO countries have about 40 thousand troops in Afghanistan, almost a quarter of them in the south.
Yet, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limits in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Specifically, they are requesting additional helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
"We will have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop made similar remarks today.
"I am not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we would need, and that's not enough, "said De Hoop to Reuters Agency at the end of the three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is passive
The past few months have also been a time of conflict between the countries involved in the issue if all the allies are actually doing their utmost in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where violence is minimal, so the combat requirements they are subject to are not as stringent as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate, "said Gates.
The British tabloid Sun described the German soldiers as lazy this week.
