State debt will rise to one trillion in 2009
The burden of a State debt in excess of 84,000 kroons is on each Czech.
Total debt rose at the end of September to DKr 842.7 billion.
This year, the government planned to borrow DKr 159.2 billion.
As a result of better-than-expected changes in government budget savings, the Ministry has reduced the projected amount to DKr 152.8 billion.
The State debt of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to DKr 842.7 billion.
During the nine months of this year it therefore increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
From June onwards, however, it decreased by SEK 13.4 billion.
Today, the Ministry of Finance has confirmed its data on State debt dating back to early October.
Each Czech is responsible for a debt in excess of 84,000 kroons.
Over the past year, the State has owed more than DKr 111 billion.
"For the time being, it seems that with a smaller deficit planned for next year, the border could be crossed by only a trillion crowns in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and a trillion crowns, "said Patria Finance analyst David Marek for the iHNed.cz server.
Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor's forecast is similar: "We could surpass the trillion in 2009.
The precise date will depend on the next budget that is not yet known.
If it appeared that the political situation was changing, that the policies were ready to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I am not waiting for this change, "he said.
Debts are growing
The state debt consists of the central government's debts and is generated mainly by the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
The Government's debt is financed by treasury bills, annuity bonds, direct loans or, for example, by loans from the European Investment Bank.
The domestic debt of the State has increased for the time being from NOK 38.5 billion to NOK 719.4 billion.
The external debt of the State has increased this year for the time being from DKr 1.7 billion to DKr 123.3 billion.
The debt of the so-called negotiable State reached at the end of September 803.3 billion kroner and from June it decreased by 13.7 billion kroner.
The average debt liability of the State was 6.5 years.
"The total debt increased annually from the first to the third half of the year by 13 per cent, which is far too high, given the current good health of the economy.
It is interesting that the increase is generated mainly by annuity securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be something to negotiate when the pension reform comes, "commented Pikora data.
Better than we expected
As a result of the Government's 2007 debt financing and management strategy, the Government planned to borrow DKr 159.2 billion this year.
At the beginning of September, however, due to better-than-expected changes in government budget savings, the Ministry reduced the projected amount to DKr 152.8 billion.
The sum is essentially constituted by the deficit in the State budget, which will obviously reach SEK 76 billion this year, instead of the originally foreseen SEK 91.3 billion.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely SEK 13.3 billion, the reserve of SEK 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of State annuities for SEK 43 billion and the repayment of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to SEK 1.8 billion.
She was appearing before a court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear.
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a Khartoum court to 15 days in prison and to deportation, his lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of letting students between the ages of 6 and 7 give the name Muhammad to a teddy bear when any representation of the Prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was subject to a penalty of whiplash.
This 54-year-old British teacher at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested on Sunday at home and charged with Islam offences and sedition under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints by parents to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually dates back to September, when this teacher asks her students, aged 6 / 7, to choose a name for the teddy bear of the class.
"Eight names come out of the mouths of the children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed," says school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the picture of the bear followed by the legend "My name is Mohamed."
The bear itself did not bear any label with this name, but the problem was simply that of the depiction of the prophet as an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in the Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," he said, it was only an "innocent mistake."
Opinion shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and "who never speaks of religion in class."
Remember that the first name Mohamed is also the middle name most given in Great Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honouring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can we, for example, give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
They did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province on Wednesday at the last negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians completed a sixth and final discussion session on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties were unable to reach a status agreement," said European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was "at stake," his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
"There is no immediate prospect of violence, but we are entering a very difficult period," he added, noting that "obvious tensions exist."
Termination of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo one last time on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Kharchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and last negotiating session since the troika was entrusted with a new mediation by the United Nations last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence to Kosovo in the Security Council, insist that negotiations continue beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," said Botsane-Kharchenko.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, Westerners believe that EU-supervised independence is the only viable solution.
Pristina stands ready to declare it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," announced the President of the Kosovo Autonomous Authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the Baden hotel, where these "last chance negotiations" have been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future Premier of the province, expressed his regret.
But he added that Belgrade's autonomy plan "belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations."
"Domino Effect"
Serbian President Boris Tadic considered that a compromise was still possible, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
Belgrade said in particular that it feared a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
"For Serbia," he said, "this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should go exclusively to the Security Council, where its Russian ally had a veto right.
"The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word"
"Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," said Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
"These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they have begun: in the Security Council. "
To the journalists, Fatmir Sedjiu had replied that "the Kosovo Parliament will have the last word on the status," adding that any unilateral declaration of independence on the part of the Albanians would be "in consultation" with the Westerners.
Bush breaks an agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
President George Bush announced, at the opening of the international peace conference convened by him on Tuesday in Annapolis, Maryland, that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately enter into negotiations with a view to finding a definitive settlement of the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do anything to help them conclude a "peace treaty" before the end of 2008.
Meanwhile, Palestinians must dismantle "terrorist infrastructure" and Israel must end its settlement activities, Bush said, reminding both parties of their obligations under the "road map" for peace that they accepted in 2003.
The Head of the White House stressed that negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority under Abbas would aim "to conclude a peace treaty that would resolve all outstanding issues, without exception, including the core issues."
This name covers the three thorny problems at the heart of the dispute between Israelis and Palestinians: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of the Arab refugees expelled from their homes in what is now the State of Israel during the 1948 conflict.
Speaking after the American President, Abbas insisted that the forthcoming negotiations be "comprehensive and thorough" and cover all aspects of a settlement, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, water, security, among others."
In turn, Olmert stood on the rostrum and pledged that the upcoming talks would be "direct and continuous" and that "an effort would be made to complete them in the course of 2008."
Bush set the deadline at the end of 2008 for the implementation of his "vision of two co-existing Palestinian and Israeli states."
Saudi Arabia revealed that it had secured a commitment to that end from Bush before deciding to participate in the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis was a success for Washington, was at the origin of a plan, endorsed by all Arab countries, that offered Israel peace in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis marks "a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, especially as it addresses the root causes of the conflict and its central aspects," says Prince Saud in his interview with the Saudi-capitalized Arabic-language daily newspaper.
