A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitlerite regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were hitherto only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his successors.
The eleven States in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, and the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out "on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the public opening up of these nominal documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental handicap of some of the victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants drawn up by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, providing proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
