Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere hostile to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought until now: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there is lightning on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has now proved this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature."
According to the famous cyprine theory, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the corner stone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If there was a life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be little living on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, temperatures of 500 degrees sometimes prevail.
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin, but she remains a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like the Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the mission ASE.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venus research, as no probe had been on its way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles do not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighbouring planet are more numerous than assumed at first.
Thus, in addition to the wind vortices already known at the North Pole, the researchers found a cloud vortex at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called an evening or morning star rotates around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly on itself: a Venetian day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and pressure of 92 bar, hardly recalls the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under similar conditions.
On both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost to space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes on Venus most of the atmosphere.
