They're not Warhols' crates.
The one who connects the Swedish concepts with the wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or do you?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden are throwing shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Stockholm Type" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes," of which the former director of the Pontus Hulten museum made a gift in 1995 at the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Stockholm Type," circulating on the international art market.
The ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created its first "Brillo-Boxes," painted wooden boxes in New York, based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powder soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
These were not works of art here, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Stockholm Type."
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum falsely claimed later that about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have transferred to him.
In truth, the 105 cases of Hulten were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that date, Warhol had already died three years ago.
Lars Byström, head curator of the Moderna Museet, examined three other Swedish private collections alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies that date back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a background layer on the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - and it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These crates were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Brillo Boxes," says moderna museum director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come another decision, the moderna museum will classify the six crates in its collection as copies / exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap cases.
But since then, we've been awning there with inexorable silence.
